AB  - This paper is motivated by empirical observations on popular-economy firms (PEFs) in the informal sector of Santiago de Chile. These are labor-managed firms (LMFs) embedded in a `popular milieu' where cooperation between their members plays a central role. This paper develops a (partial equilibrium) microeconomic theory of PEFs. Endogeneizing the level of cooperation between the workers, the paper develops a static and a dynamic model to analyze whether embeddedness influences the behavior of the PEF. Embeddedness is assumed to be captured by three different characteristics suggested by the empirical observations. Most of them influence the employment and income levels in the PEF.
